Subject: Re: [T2] re:Old Paint

 I disagree on this thought process.

Paint oxidizes because the sun has dried it out, and all is left on the
surface is the dried out pigment.

That's why it's called oxidized paint.

I could possibly be wet sanded, and clear coated, but their are two
chances of getting an even color, over the whole bus with the old paint
-- (1) slim, (2) none.    

You cannot rub an old finish with compound and then clear over the
polished surface---the clear would be blowing off in sheets, without
giving the base paint any biter's---it must be abraded with a scuffing,
or sanding, therefore removing more of what you didn't have in the first
place--paint.

I do agree however that a good Carnuba wax is probably the best--however
read what's in all the waxes---"Petroleum Distillates", which in common
terms is mineral spirits---
It along with whatever wax is in the stuff, makes the paint look
slick---but as soon as the wax and solvent's dry up from the sun--your
back to square one--dried up, oxidized paint.

My suggestion---forget the whole process, and get down and dirty--paint
it.


Later,


Terry the Painter


 
