Brandt - 
Here's my .02 : 
Paint never really dries completely. As the base lacquer (what was
originally used on buses) evaporates over time, oxidation takes place
with the remaining pigment, hence the oxidized film on old paint.
Whether it can be buffed out depends on how thick the remaining paint
is. It's often very easy to buff right thru to bare metal or primer at
the very least.Try it in a small spot first. 
However, if there is a sufficient thickness left, you can try one of the
following methods: 
1) Clean the bus THOROUGHLY, first with a good quality car wash soap and
water. Do this in the shade so you don't bake soap and old dirt into the
old paint. Make sure you get all the nooks and crannies. 2)Clean the
surface again, this time with a good quality dewaxer/degreaser and a
paper towel. Allow it to dry before proceeding. 
3) Remove the oxidation with HAND compound. Machine compound on a buffer
will take it down to metal.Red is for heavy oxidation, white for lesser
damage. 4)If, after all this work, the surface is smooth and even,
proceed to the next step. If not, or if the surface is too thin, you
will need to repaint - at least you've prepped it well :) 
5)Compounding alone will not stop oxidation; it only removes the already
oxidized paint. At this stage, put on a nice coat of hand glaze. This
seals the surface and evens out small pits. After this has dried to a
haze and been bufed with a terry towel, proceed to wax the finish. By
this time it should look pretty good. 6)Use a good quality carnauba wax.
That's all you need 
- no snake oil, miracle claim stuff please. Again, let it dry to a haze
and buff with a dry terry towel. This will stop oxidation for a while,
but like anything else, not permanently. Remember to wash the car often
(always with good quality soap) and wax it - but don't wax more than 4
times a year; the buildup is a b!(-at-)#% to get off. 
7) Finally, another option is to clearcoat the finish after step 4.
Urethane clear will work well over old, CLEAN lacquer; make sure this is
what you have to avoid compatibilty problems. 
It takes quite a bit to restore an old finish - I set aside a full
weekend for the above. It can be worth the effort and of course nice
original paint is a good thing. Cost? Maybe a hundred bucks for all the
necessary materials (don't cut corners here). Clearcoat? 60-100 bucks
for urethane; DON'T do it yourself if you don't have the suit and air
supply. A good shop will charge you $6-800 for the task, more if you
haven't done a decent prep job. 
Hope this helps! 
Tom
71 Campmobile w/crummy paint :) 
